{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0df70f0c-1f09-4f50-9846-275970e6349f","content":"CLR activation logs won't help here. They only cover **runtime loading** — which CLR version the shim selects, whether the runtime loads at all, etc. They don't contain any information about application-level exceptions like `NullReferenceException`.\n\n**To diagnose a `NullReferenceException`, try these instead:**\n\n1. **Stack trace** — check the exception's stack trace to find the exact line/method.\n2. **Debugger** — attach Visual Studio or `dotnet-dump` to inspect the null reference.\n3. **Logging** — add logging around startup to identify which object is null.\n4. **`dotnet-dump collect`** — capture a dump on crash for post-mortem analysis.\n\nWould you like help with any of these approaches? For example, I can help you set up crash dump collection or analyze a stack trace if you share one.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8abd440e-400e-454f-b21d-2149fed13fc8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which is described as: \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with runtime loading/selection — things like which CLR version gets loaded, shim behavior, etc. A NullReferenceException is an application-level bug, not a runtime activation problem.\n\n\nI should explain to the user why this skill isn't applicable to their situation rather than trying to force it.","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"6088:3FDA7D:10367D6:1478490:69FFE098"},"id":"0b480e5c-fb0a-42de-90c1-4a23725ac456","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:34:28.986Z","parentId":"885a3521-9594-4fb8-bb09-004e57a2b22a